description:
DOM = Document Object Model — the browser's in-memory tree of HTML elements.

SELECTING ELEMENTS:
  document.getElementById('id')
  document.querySelector('.class')      // first match
  document.querySelectorAll('div')      // NodeList of all

MODIFYING ELEMENTS:
  el.textContent = 'new text';          // safe (escapes HTML)
  el.innerHTML   = '<b>bold</b>';       // renders HTML (XSS risk)
  el.style.color = 'red';
  el.classList.add('active');
  el.classList.toggle('hidden');
  el.setAttribute('data-id', '42');

CREATING & REMOVING:
  const div = document.createElement('div');
  div.textContent = 'Hello';
  parent.appendChild(div);
  parent.removeChild(div);

EVENTS:
  el.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();   // stop default action (form submit, link follow)
    e.stopPropagation();  // stop bubbling up to parent
    console.log(e.target); // element that was clicked
  });

EVENT DELEGATION:
  // Instead of adding listener to each child, add one to parent:
  ul.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
    if (e.target.tagName === 'LI') {
      handle(e.target);
    }
  });

COMMON EVENTS: click, dblclick, keydown, keyup, input, change, submit, focus, blur, mouseover, resize, scroll, DOMContentLoaded

ES6 (2015) modernised JavaScript. These features are used in every React codebase.

ARROW FUNCTIONS:
  // Traditional
  function add(a, b) { return a + b; }
  // Arrow
  const add = (a, b) => a + b;
  // Single param — no parens needed
  const double = n => n * 2;
  // Key difference: arrow functions do NOT have their own 'this'

DESTRUCTURING:
  const { name, age } = person;         // object
  const [first, , third] = array;       // array (skip index 1)
  const { a: alias } = obj;            // rename while destructuring

SPREAD & REST:
  const merged = { ...obj1, ...obj2 };  // spread objects
  const arr2   = [...arr1, 4, 5];       // spread arrays
  function sum(...nums) { }             // rest: collect into array

TEMPLATE LITERALS:
  const msg = `Hello ${name}, you are ${age} years old`;

PROMISES:
  const p = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    setTimeout(() => resolve('done'), 1000);
  });
  p.then(val => console.log(val))
   .catch(err => console.error(err));

ASYNC/AWAIT:
  async function fetchData() {
    try {
      const res = await fetch('/api/data');
      const json = await res.json();
      return json;
    } catch (err) {
      console.error(err);
    }
  }

MODULES (ESM):
  // export (named)
  export const PI = 3.14;
  export function greet(name) { }
  // export (default)
  export default class App { }
  // import
  import App, { PI, greet } from './module.js';

OTHER ES6+:
• Optional chaining: obj?.prop?.nested
• Nullish coalescing: value ?? 'default'
• Map, Set, WeakMap, WeakSet
• Symbol, Iterator, Generator

ASYNCHRONOUS PROGRAMMING:

Why async? Browser JS is single-threaded. Network calls, timers, and I/O are offloaded to browser APIs and handled via the Event Loop when complete.

Event Loop flow:
  Call Stack → Web APIs → Callback Queue → Call Stack (when empty)
  Microtasks (Promises) → Macrotasks (setTimeout)

FETCH API:
  // GET
  fetch('https://api.example.com/users')
    .then(res => {
      if (!res.ok) throw new Error('HTTP ' + res.status);
      return res.json();
    })
    .then(data => console.log(data))
    .catch(err => console.error(err));

  // POST
  fetch('/api/users', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json',
               'Authorization': 'Bearer ' + token },
    body: JSON.stringify({ name: 'Alice', age: 25 })
  }).then(res => res.json());

  // Async/await style (cleaner)
  async function createUser(user) {
    const res = await fetch('/api/users', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify(user)
    });
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(await res.text());
    return res.json();
  }

PROMISE COMBINATORS:
  Promise.all([p1, p2, p3])      // wait for ALL — fails fast on any rejection
  Promise.allSettled([p1, p2])   // wait for ALL — get all results/errors
  Promise.race([p1, p2])         // first to settle wins
  Promise.any([p1, p2])          // first to RESOLVE wins

ERROR HANDLING PATTERN:
  fetch() only rejects on network failure, NOT on 4xx/5xx.
  Always check res.ok or res.status.

LIFECYCLE (class component mental model):
  Mount   → componentDidMount   (run once after render)
  Update  → componentDidUpdate  (run after re-render)
  Unmount → componentWillUnmount (cleanup)

HOOKS (modern equivalent):

useState — local state
  const [value, setValue] = useState(initial);

useEffect — side effects (data fetch, subscriptions, DOM manipulation)
  useEffect(() => {
    // Runs after render
    fetchData().then(setData);

    return () => {
      // Cleanup: runs before unmount or before re-running effect
      subscription.unsubscribe();
    };
  }, [dependency1, dependency2]);  // re-runs when deps change
  // [] = run once on mount only
  // no array = run after every render

useRef — mutable ref that does NOT cause re-render
  const inputRef = useRef(null);
  <input ref={inputRef} />
  inputRef.current.focus(); // access DOM node

useCallback — memoize a function reference
  const handleClick = useCallback(() => doSomething(id), [id]);

useMemo — memoize a computed value
  const expensiveResult = useMemo(() => compute(data), [data]);

CUSTOM HOOKS:
  Reusable logic extracted into a function prefixed with 'use'.
  function useFetch(url) {
    const [data, setData] = useState(null);
    const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
    useEffect(() => {
      fetch(url).then(r => r.json()).then(d => {
        setData(d);
        setLoading(false);
      });
    }, [url]);
    return { data, loading };
  }

RULES OF HOOKS:
• Only call hooks at the top level (not inside loops/conditions)
• Only call hooks from React functions (not regular JS functions)

PROBLEM WITH PROP DRILLING:
Passing props through many levels:
  App → Layout → Main → Section → Card → Button
Becomes messy when deeply nested components need the same data.

CONTEXT API (built into React):
  // 1. Create context
  const ThemeContext = createContext('light');

  // 2. Provide it
  function App() {
    const [theme, setTheme] = useState('light');
    return (
      <ThemeContext.Provider value={{ theme, setTheme }}>
        <Layout />
      </ThemeContext.Provider>
    );
  }

  // 3. Consume anywhere in tree
  function Button() {
    const { theme } = useContext(ThemeContext);
    return <button className={theme}>Click</button>;
  }

WHEN TO USE CONTEXT: global data like theme, auth user, language, settings.

REDUX:
For complex state with many interactions. Used in large enterprise apps.
  Store: single source of truth for all app state
  Action: plain object describing what happened { type: 'ADD_ITEM', payload: item }
  Reducer: pure function (state, action) => newState
  Dispatch: send an action to the store

REDUX TOOLKIT (modern Redux):
  import { createSlice, configureStore } from '@reduxjs/toolkit';
  const counterSlice = createSlice({
    name: 'counter',
    initialState: { value: 0 },
    reducers: {
      increment: state => { state.value += 1; }
    }
  });

WHEN TO USE REDUX:
• Multiple components need to share and mutate the same state
• Complex state transitions that need to be tracked/debugged
• Large teams where predictable state flow matters

ALTERNATIVES: Zustand (lightweight), Jotai, React Query (for server state)

React Router enables client-side routing — navigating between pages without a full page reload.

INSTALL: npm install react-router-dom

BASIC SETUP:
  import { BrowserRouter, Routes, Route, Link, useNavigate, useParams } from 'react-router-dom';

  function App() {
    return (
      <BrowserRouter>
        <Routes>
          <Route path="/"           element={<Home />} />
          <Route path="/about"      element={<About />} />
          <Route path="/users/:id"  element={<UserDetail />} />
          <Route path="*"           element={<NotFound />} />
        </Routes>
      </BrowserRouter>
    );
  }

NAVIGATION:
  // Declarative (renders <a> tag)
  <Link to="/about">About</Link>

  // Programmatic
  const navigate = useNavigate();
  navigate('/dashboard');         // push
  navigate(-1);                   // go back
  navigate('/login', { replace: true }); // replace history entry

ROUTE PARAMS:
  // Route: /users/:id
  const { id } = useParams();  // id = '42' for /users/42

QUERY PARAMS:
  const [searchParams] = useSearchParams();
  const query = searchParams.get('q');  // /search?q=react

NESTED ROUTES:
  <Route path="/dashboard" element={<Dashboard />}>
    <Route path="profile" element={<Profile />} />
    <Route path="settings" element={<Settings />} />
  </Route>
  // Dashboard uses <Outlet /> to render nested route

PROTECTED ROUTES:
  function PrivateRoute({ children }) {
    const { user } = useAuth();
    return user ? children : <Navigate to="/login" />;
  }

React apps consume Spring Boot REST APIs. Two common approaches:

FETCH (built-in, no install):
  useEffect(() => {
    fetch('http://localhost:8080/api/users')
      .then(res => {
        if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Failed');
        return res.json();
      })
      .then(data => setUsers(data))
      .catch(err => setError(err.message));
  }, []);

AXIOS (install: npm install axios):
  import axios from 'axios';
  useEffect(() => {
    axios.get('http://localhost:8080/api/users')
      .then(res => setUsers(res.data))  // res.data is already parsed
      .catch(err => setError(err.message));
  }, []);

AXIOS ADVANTAGES OVER FETCH:
• Automatic JSON parsing (no .json() call)
• Automatic error for 4xx/5xx status
• Request/Response interceptors (add auth headers globally)
• Request cancellation with AbortController
• Base URL configuration

AXIOS INSTANCE (for Spring Boot):
  const api = axios.create({
    baseURL: 'http://localhost:8080/api',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' }
  });
  // Interceptor to add JWT token
  api.interceptors.request.use(config => {
    const token = localStorage.getItem('token');
    if (token) config.headers.Authorization = `Bearer ${token}`;
    return config;
  });

CRUD PATTERN:
  api.get('/users')              // GET all
  api.get('/users/42')           // GET one
  api.post('/users', { name })   // POST create
  api.put('/users/42', data)     // PUT update
  api.delete('/users/42')        // DELETE

LOADING STATE PATTERN:
  const [data, setData]       = useState(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError]     = useState(null);
  // Show loading spinner, then data or error

PERFORMANCE OPTIMIZATION:

React.memo — prevent re-render if props unchanged:
  const Card = React.memo(function Card({ title }) {
    return <div>{title}</div>;
  });

useMemo — memoize expensive computation:
  const sortedList = useMemo(() => [...list].sort(), [list]);

useCallback — stable function reference for child components:
  const handleDelete = useCallback((id) => {
    setItems(items.filter(i => i.id !== id));
  }, [items]);

Lazy loading (code splitting):
  const HeavyComponent = React.lazy(() => import('./HeavyComponent'));
  // Wrap in Suspense:
  <Suspense fallback={<Spinner />}>
    <HeavyComponent />
  </Suspense>

Virtualization (for long lists):
  Use react-window or react-virtual to render only visible rows.
  Critical for tables with 1000+ rows.

ERROR BOUNDARIES:
Class component that catches JS errors in its child tree.
  class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {
    state = { hasError: false };
    static getDerivedStateFromError(error) {
      return { hasError: true };
    }
    componentDidCatch(error, info) {
      logToSentry(error, info);
    }
    render() {
      if (this.state.hasError) return <h1>Something went wrong.</h1>;
      return this.props.children;
    }
  }
  // Usage:
  <ErrorBoundary>
    <MyRiskyComponent />
  </ErrorBoundary>

NOTE: Error boundaries only catch errors during render/lifecycle, not in event handlers or async code.

FOUR PILLARS OF OOP:

1. ENCAPSULATION
   Private fields + public getters/setters
   class Account {
     private double balance;
     public double getBalance() { return balance; }
     public void deposit(double amount) {
       if (amount > 0) balance += amount;
     }
   }

2. INHERITANCE
   class Animal { void speak() { } }
   class Dog extends Animal {
     @Override void speak() { System.out.println("Woof"); }
   }
   • Java supports single inheritance (one parent class)
   • Multiple inheritance via interfaces

3. POLYMORPHISM
   Animal a = new Dog();  // runtime polymorphism
   a.speak();             // calls Dog.speak() — dynamic dispatch
   // Compile-time: method overloading (same name, different params)

4. ABSTRACTION
   • Abstract class: cannot be instantiated, may have abstract methods
   • Interface: contract — all methods implicitly public abstract (pre-Java 8)

KEY KEYWORDS:
  this  — reference to current object instance
  super — reference to parent class; super() calls parent constructor
  static — belongs to class, not instance
  final — variable: constant; method: cannot override; class: cannot extend

CLASS MEMBERS:
  class Person {
    private String name;          // field
    public Person(String name) {  // constructor
      this.name = name;
    }
    public String getName() { return name; }  // method
    static int count = 0;         // static field
  }

INTERFACE vs ABSTRACT CLASS:
  Interface: no state (fields must be static final), multiple inheritance
  Abstract class: can have state, constructors, concrete methods
  Java 8+: interfaces can have default and static methods

EXCEPTION HIERARCHY:
  Throwable
  ├── Error (JVM errors — don't catch: OutOfMemoryError, StackOverflowError)
  └── Exception
      ├── Checked (must handle: IOException, SQLException)
      └── RuntimeException (Unchecked: NullPointerException, ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException)

SYNTAX:
  try {
    // risky code
    int result = 10 / divisor;
  } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Division by zero: " + e.getMessage());
  } catch (Exception e) {
    e.printStackTrace();  // log the full stack trace
  } finally {
    // always runs — use for resource cleanup
    connection.close();
  }

TRY-WITH-RESOURCES (Java 7+):
  try (FileReader fr = new FileReader("file.txt")) {
    // fr is automatically closed after block
  }  // implements AutoCloseable

throws vs throw:
  // throws: declares checked exceptions method can propagate
  public void readFile(String path) throws IOException { }
  // throw: actually throws an exception
  throw new IllegalArgumentException("Name cannot be null");

CUSTOM EXCEPTIONS:
  class InsufficientFundsException extends RuntimeException {
    private final double amount;
    public InsufficientFundsException(double amount) {
      super("Insufficient funds. Needed: " + amount);
      this.amount = amount;
    }
    public double getAmount() { return amount; }
  }
  // Usage:
  throw new InsufficientFundsException(500.0);

SPRING BOOT EXCEPTION HANDLING:
  @RestControllerAdvice
  public class GlobalExceptionHandler {
    @ExceptionHandler(InsufficientFundsException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponse> handle(InsufficientFundsException e) {
      return ResponseEntity.badRequest().body(new ErrorResponse(e.getMessage()));
    }
  }

COLLECTIONS HIERARCHY:
  Collection
  ├── List — ordered, allows duplicates
  │   ├── ArrayList  — dynamic array, O(1) get, O(n) insert middle
  │   ├── LinkedList — doubly linked, O(1) insert/delete, O(n) get
  │   └── Vector     — synchronized ArrayList (legacy)
  ├── Set — no duplicates
  │   ├── HashSet    — O(1) ops, unordered
  │   ├── LinkedHashSet — preserves insertion order
  │   └── TreeSet    — sorted, O(log n) ops
  └── Queue
      ├── LinkedList  — also Queue/Deque
      ├── PriorityQueue — min-heap by default
      └── ArrayDeque  — fast stack/queue operations

  Map (not Collection)
  ├── HashMap      — O(1) avg, unordered, allows null key
  ├── LinkedHashMap — preserves insertion order
  ├── TreeMap      — sorted by key, O(log n)
  └── Hashtable    — synchronized, legacy (use ConcurrentHashMap instead)

COMPARABLE vs COMPARATOR:
  // Comparable — natural ordering (in the class itself)
  class Employee implements Comparable<Employee> {
    public int compareTo(Employee o) {
      return this.salary - o.salary;  // ascending by salary
    }
  }
  Collections.sort(list);  // uses compareTo

  // Comparator — external / custom ordering
  Comparator<Employee> byName = (a, b) -> a.name.compareTo(b.name);
  list.sort(byName);
  // Or: Comparator.comparing(Employee::getName).reversed()

GENERICS:
  List<String> names = new ArrayList<>();   // type-safe
  Map<String, Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();
  public <T> T findFirst(List<T> list) { return list.get(0); }
  // Bounded: <T extends Number> — T must be Number or subclass

FILE HANDLING:
  // Read all lines
  List<String> lines = Files.readAllLines(Path.of("file.txt"));
  // Write
  Files.writeString(Path.of("out.txt"), content);
  // Stream lines (large files)
  Files.lines(path).forEach(System.out::println);

MEMORY & GC:
  Heap: new objects go here; GC reclaims unreachable objects
  Stack: method calls and local primitives
  GC types: Serial, Parallel, G1 (default Java 9+), ZGC (low-latency)
  Prevent leaks: close streams, remove listeners, avoid static collections

LAMBDA EXPRESSIONS:
A concise way to write anonymous functions.

  // Before Java 8
  Runnable r = new Runnable() {
    public void run() { System.out.println("Hello"); }
  };

  // Java 8 lambda
  Runnable r = () -> System.out.println("Hello");

SYNTAX:
  (params) -> expression
  (params) -> { statements; return value; }
  param -> expression  // single param, no parens

FUNCTIONAL INTERFACES (java.util.function):
  @FunctionalInterface = interface with exactly ONE abstract method

  Function<T,R>     — takes T, returns R   — apply()
  Consumer<T>       — takes T, returns void — accept()
  Supplier<T>       — takes nothing, returns T — get()
  Predicate<T>      — takes T, returns boolean — test()
  BiFunction<T,U,R> — takes T and U, returns R

EXAMPLES:
  Function<String, Integer> len = s -> s.length();
  len.apply("hello");  // 5

  Predicate<Integer> isEven = n -> n % 2 == 0;
  isEven.test(4);  // true

  Consumer<String> print = System.out::println;
  print.accept("hi");

  Supplier<List<String>> newList = ArrayList::new;

METHOD REFERENCES (shorthand for lambdas):
  // Static method
  Function<String, Integer> f = Integer::parseInt;
  // Instance method (object)
  Consumer<String> print = System.out::println;
  // Instance method (class)
  Function<String, String> upper = String::toUpperCase;
  // Constructor
  Supplier<ArrayList> create = ArrayList::new;

COMPOSING FUNCTIONS:
  Function<Integer, Integer> doubleIt = x -> x * 2;
  Function<Integer, Integer> addTen  = x -> x + 10;
  Function<Integer, Integer> both = doubleIt.andThen(addTen);  // double THEN add
  both.apply(5);  // (5*2)+10 = 20

OPTIONAL:
A container that may or may not hold a non-null value.
Eliminate NullPointerException from your codebase.

  Optional<String> name = Optional.of("Alice");      // must be non-null
  Optional<String> empty = Optional.empty();
  Optional<String> nullable = Optional.ofNullable(getValue()); // safe

  // Consuming safely
  name.isPresent()                     // true/false check
  name.get()                           // throws if empty — avoid!
  name.orElse("default")              // value or default
  name.orElseGet(() -> computeDefault()) // lazy default
  name.orElseThrow(NoSuchElementException::new)
  name.map(String::toUpperCase)        // transform if present
  name.filter(n -> n.length() > 3)     // filter
  name.ifPresent(System.out::println)  // consume if present

  // Chaining
  Optional<String> city = Optional.ofNullable(user)
    .map(User::getAddress)
    .map(Address::getCity);

DATE & TIME API (java.time — Java 8):
Replaces the broken java.util.Date and Calendar.

  LocalDate    — date only (2024-01-15)
  LocalTime    — time only (14:30:00)
  LocalDateTime — date + time (2024-01-15T14:30:00)
  ZonedDateTime — with timezone
  Instant      — machine timestamp (epoch milliseconds)
  Duration     — time-based amount (hours, minutes, seconds)
  Period       — date-based amount (years, months, days)

EXAMPLES:
  LocalDate today = LocalDate.now();
  LocalDate dob   = LocalDate.of(2000, 3, 15);
  Period age = Period.between(dob, today);
  System.out.println(age.getYears()); // years old

  LocalDateTime dt = LocalDateTime.now();
  dt.plusDays(7);         // immutable — returns new instance
  dt.format(DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("dd/MM/yyyy HH:mm"));

  // Convert to legacy Date
  Date legacy = Date.from(Instant.now());

CALLABLE & FUTURE:
  Callable<String> task = () -> longRunningOp();
  ExecutorService exec = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(4);
  Future<String> future = exec.submit(task);
  String result = future.get();  // blocks until done

COMPLETABLE FUTURE:
  CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> fetchUser(id))
    .thenApply(user -> user.getName().toUpperCase())
    .thenAccept(System.out::println)
    .exceptionally(ex -> { log(ex); return null; });

  // Combine
  CompletableFuture.allOf(cf1, cf2, cf3).thenRun(() -> done());

VAR (Java 10) — local type inference:
  var list = new ArrayList<String>();  // inferred as ArrayList<String>
  var map  = new HashMap<String, Integer>();
  // Only for local variables — NOT fields or return types
  // Makes code shorter without losing type safety

SWITCH EXPRESSIONS (Java 14):
  // Old switch (statement)
  String result;
  switch (day) {
    case MON: result = "Weekday"; break;
    case SAT: result = "Weekend"; break;
    default:  result = "Other";
  }

  // New switch (expression) — no fall-through, returns value
  String result = switch (day) {
    case MON, TUE, WED, THU, FRI -> "Weekday";
    case SAT, SUN                  -> "Weekend";
  };

TEXT BLOCKS (Java 15):
  // Old: escaping hell
  String json = "{\"name\": \"Alice\", \"age\": 25}";

  // New: text block (triple quotes)
  String json = """
      {
          "name": "Alice",
          "age": 25
      }
      """;
  // Indentation is stripped relative to closing """

RECORDS (Java 16):
  // Immutable data classes — replaces verbose POJOs
  record Point(int x, int y) { }  // auto-generates: constructor, getters, equals, hashCode, toString

  Point p = new Point(3, 4);
  p.x();   // getter (not getX())
  p.y();
  // Compact canonical constructor for validation:
  record Range(int min, int max) {
    Range {
      if (min > max) throw new IllegalArgumentException();
    }
  }

IMMUTABLE COLLECTIONS (Java 9):
  List.of("a", "b", "c")      // unmodifiable
  Set.of(1, 2, 3)
  Map.of("k1", "v1", "k2", "v2")

COLLECTORS API:
  Collectors.toList()          // collect to list
  Collectors.toUnmodifiableList()  // Java 10
  Collectors.joining(", ")    // join strings
  Collectors.groupingBy()      // group by key
  Collectors.partitioningBy()  // split by predicate
  Collectors.counting()        // count per group
  Collectors.summingInt()      // sum per group

LOGGING WITH LOG4J:
  // pom.xml dependency: log4j-core
  Logger logger = LogManager.getLogger(MyClass.class);
  logger.info("Processing request for user {}", userId);
  logger.error("Database error", exception);
  logger.debug("SQL: {}", query);  // only logs in debug level

IOC (INVERSION OF CONTROL):
Traditionally, your code creates its own dependencies:
  UserService service = new UserService(new UserRepository(...));

With IOC, the framework creates and manages objects (called beans):
  @Service class UserService { ... }  // Spring creates and manages this

DEPENDENCY INJECTION (DI):
Spring injects dependencies into your objects automatically.

  @Service
  public class OrderService {
    private final UserRepository userRepo;
    private final EmailService emailService;

    // Constructor injection (PREFERRED)
    public OrderService(UserRepository userRepo, EmailService emailService) {
      this.userRepo     = userRepo;
      this.emailService = emailService;
    }
  }

SPRING BEANS:
  @Component   — generic Spring bean
  @Service     — business logic layer
  @Repository  — data access layer (adds exception translation)
  @Controller  — MVC controller
  @RestController — REST controller (@Controller + @ResponseBody)
  @Configuration — Java config class
  @Bean          — factory method in @Configuration class

SPRING MVC REQUEST FLOW:
  HTTP Request
    → DispatcherServlet (front controller)
    → HandlerMapping (finds @RequestMapping method)
    → Controller method executes
    → ViewResolver (for MVC) / MessageConverter (for REST)
    → HTTP Response

SPRING BOOT:
  Spring Boot = Spring + autoconfiguration + embedded server.
  No XML config. No WAR deployment. Just run the main class.
  @SpringBootApplication = @Configuration + @EnableAutoConfiguration + @ComponentScan

  @SpringBootApplication
  public class App {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
      SpringApplication.run(App.class, args);
    }
  }

REST PRINCIPLES:
